const summary = "'`Dataset ds001_aml contained ${r.n} patients and one binary outcome, objective_response. The overall response rate was ${r.outcome_rate.toFixed(4)}. I decoded the local Parquet file and tested main effects, subgroup heterogeneity, and interactions using response-rate contrasts and linear probability models; p-values are exploratory and mostly unadjusted unless explicitly described as adjusted.

Main effects: feature_027 had the strongest monotone association. Response fell from ${r.feature_027.rates[0].rate.toFixed(3)} at level 0 to ${r.feature_027.rates[1].rate.toFixed(3)} at level 1 and ${r.feature_027.rates[2].rate.toFixed(3)} at level 2, with an effect of ${r.feature_027.ordinal.effect.toFixed(4)} per level (p=${r.feature_027.ordinal.p.toExponential(2)}). The strongest binary positive main effects were feature_025 (effect ${r.main_named.feature_025.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.main_named.feature_025.p.toExponential(2)}), feature_015 (effect ${r.main_named.feature_015.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.main_named.feature_015.p.toExponential(2)}), and feature_023 (effect ${r.main_named.feature_023.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.main_named.feature_023.p.toExponential(2)}). Negative binary main effects were feature_001 (effect ${r.main_named.feature_001.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.main_named.feature_001.p.toExponential(2)}) and feature_032 (effect ${r.main_named.feature_032.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.main_named.feature_032.p.toExponential(2)}). Feature_044 showed no meaningful main effect per 10 units (effect ${r.feature_044.effect.toFixed(5)}, p=${r.feature_044.p.toFixed(3)}).

Continuous features: feature_004, feature_031, feature_059, feature_033, and feature_053 all showed significant univariable associations. The directions were lower response with higher feature_004 (effect ${c004.effect.toFixed(4)} per unit), lower response with higher feature_031 (effect ${(c031.effect * 10).toFixed(4)} per 10 units), higher response with higher feature_059 (effect ${c059.effect.toFixed(4)} per unit), lower response with higher feature_033 (effect ${c033.effect.toFixed(5)} per unit), and lower response with higher feature_053 (effect ${r.feature_053.effect.toFixed(4)} per 10 units). In the extended adjusted model, these directions remained significant except feature_044, which stayed null.

The most important interaction pattern involved feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023. Pairwise screens initially showed large positive interactions among these variables, especially feature_015 x feature_025 (DID ${r.named_interactions.feature_015_feature_025.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.named_interactions.feature_015_feature_025.p.toExponential(2)}), feature_025 x feature_023 (DID ${r.named_interactions.feature_025_feature_023.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.named_interactions.feature_025_feature_023.p.toExponential(2)}), and feature_015 x feature_023 (DID ${r.named_interactions.feature_015_feature_023.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.named_interactions.feature_015_feature_023.p.toExponential(2)}). Subgroup testing refined this: feature_015 had almost no effect when feature_025=0 (effect ${r.subgroups.feature_015_with_feature_025_0.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.subgroups.feature_015_with_feature_025_0.p.toFixed(3)}) but a large positive effect when feature_025=1 (effect ${r.subgroups.feature_015_with_feature_025_1.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.subgroups.feature_015_with_feature_025_1.p.toExponential(2)}).

The refined multivariable interaction model showed that the apparent pairwise effects were largely driven by a three-way pattern. Patients with feature_015=1, feature_025=1, and feature_023=1 had response ${combo111.rate.toFixed(3)} (n=${combo111.n}), versus ${otherRate.toFixed(3)} among all other patients, an absolute difference of ${tripleVsOtherEffect.toFixed(3)}. In a model containing all three main effects, all pairwise terms, the three-way term, feature_001, feature_032, and feature_027, the three-way coefficient was ${r.top_three_interaction_ols.feature_015_x_feature_025_x_feature_023.beta.toFixed(4)} (p=${r.top_three_interaction_ols.feature_015_x_feature_025_x_feature_023.p.toExponential(2)}), while the pairwise terms became nonsignificant. This suggests a high-response subgroup defined by simultaneous positivity for all three features rather than three independent pairwise synergies.

Negative-effect heterogeneity was also present. feature_001 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction ${i001025.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${i001025.p.toExponential(2)}), feature_032 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction ${i025032.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${i025032.p.toExponential(2)}), and feature_032 attenuated the feature_015 association (interaction ${i015032.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${i015032.p.toExponential(2)}). The two negative main-effect features feature_001 and feature_032 did not show evidence of an additional negative interaction with each other (interaction ${r.named_interactions.feature_001_feature_032.effect.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.named_interactions.feature_001_feature_032.p.toFixed(3)}).

Subgroup checks across feature_027 did not show statistically significant modification of the feature_015 effect by feature_027 (interaction ${r.ordinal_interactions.feature_015_feature_027.interaction.beta.toFixed(4)}, p=${r.ordinal_interactions.feature_015_feature_027.interaction.p.toFixed(3)}); feature_015 was positive at all feature_027 levels. Nominal continuous-by-binary interactions were detected for feature_044 by feature_066 (slope difference ${r.cont_interactions_044_top[0].effect.toFixed(4)} per 10 units, p=${r.cont_interactions_044_top[0].p.toFixed(4)}) and feature_053 by feature_068 (slope difference ${r.cont_interactions_053_top[0].effect.toFixed(4)} per 10 units, p=${r.cont_interactions_053_top[0].p.toFixed(4)}), but these were weaker exploratory findings.

Overall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is dominated by a strong low-response gradient across feature_027, independent continuous adverse associations involving feature_004, feature_031, feature_033, and feature_053, a positive continuous association with feature_059, and a striking high-response subgroup where feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023 are all present. The strongest treatment-biomarker-like relationship is the three-feature interaction; isolated positivity for only one or two of those features does not reproduce the same high response rate.'"\\n"'`;
fs.writeFileSync('"'analysis_summary.txt', summary, 'utf8');
